  "prompt": "My father wants me to be an engineer but I want to be a writer. Currently, I am in first year of engineering. Should I quit engineering or obey my father?",
  "response": "This is a deeply personal decision, and there is no one-size-fits-all answer. However, here are some considerations to help you make a choice that aligns with your values, goals, and circumstances:\n\n### 1. **Understand Your Passions and Goals**\n   - If writing is your true passion, ask yourself if it\u2019s something you can see yourself building a career around. Writing can be fulfilling but often requires persistence, creativity, and sometimes financial flexibility.\n   - Engineering, on the other hand, is a stable and rewarding career that can provide financial security. Consider if there\u2019s a way to balance both interests\u2014like technical writing or pursuing writing as a side hustle while working in engineering.\n\n### 2. **Communicate with Your Father**\n   - Share your feelings with your father in a calm, respectful way. Explain why writing is important to you and how you envision your future. Parents often want what they believe is best for their children, and understanding your perspective might help him see your point of view.\n   - If possible, propose a compromise, such as completing your engineering degree while pursuing writing on the side.\n\n### 3. **Evaluate Practicalities**\n   - Think about the financial and career implications of quitting engineering. Starting over in a new field might require additional education or time to establish yourself.\n   - If you decide to stay in engineering, consider how you can incorporate writing into your life\u2014through blogging, freelancing, or creative projects.\n\n### 4. **Consider the Long-Term**\n   - Reflect on where you see yourself in 5, 10, or 20 years. Will you regret not pursuing writing? Or will you appreciate the stability and opportunities that engineering provides?\n   - Keep in mind that many people change careers later in life, so your current decision doesn\u2019t have to define your entire future.\n\n### 5. **Seek Advice and Support**\n   - Talk to mentors, career counselors, or people who work in fields you\u2019re interested in. They can provide insights into the realities of both engineering and writing careers.\n   - Consider joining writing groups or communities to connect with others who share your passion.\n\n### 6. **Experiment Before Deciding**\n   - Use your current situation as an opportunity to explore both fields. Take writing courses, start a blog, or submit work to publications while continuing your engineering studies. This can help you clarify what you truly want.\n\nUltimately, the decision is yours. While it\u2019s important to consider your father\u2019s wishes, it\u2019s equally important to pursue a life that feels meaningful and fulfilling to you. Whether you choose engineering, writing, or a combination of both, approach it with intention and commitment.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
